<br>
Her captors were taking no chances with her now.  A grim smile touched the corner of her split and bleeding lips.  An entire regiment of Dark Minions (Mostly Orcs) had been put to death today because for a short time, she had actually escaped.<br>
No one EVER escapes from the prisons of the Halls of the Dead.  Thus, her small triumph was all the sweeter.<br>
<br>
She shifted again, trying to find a position a little less uncomfortable.  The simple act of breathing was becoming agony.  Centuri knew she had a couple of broken ribs as well as the collection of whip-welts, cuts and bruises from the last few days.  Somehow, her captors were blocking her prayers of healing.  She hadn’t been in this constant a state of pain since she had learned her first healing spell.  She squinted into the darkness with her one good eye, the other one being completely swollen shut.  Ah well, there really wasn’t anything to see anyhow.<br>
<br>
Ah, but what a day!  Worth every drop of her spilled blood.<br>
A clerical error had put her in one of the minimally guarded detention areas meant for the weakest of the slaves.  Lucky chance had placed her next to the guard station.  A prayer and a softly whispered song lulled the single guard to sleep.  The guard’s own dagger ensured he would never waken.  His dark, hooded cloak aided Centuri in slipping through the dark hallways, just another servant, scuttling off on just another errand, eternally in fear of her masters.<br>
The god of Mischief must have walked beside her, laughing.  It was nearly 2 full hours before her absence was discovered.  More than enough time for her to gather information and arrange for a message to be sent.  They caught her soon after. Not surprising considering how they out-numbered her.  The subsequent beating she endured at the hands of the guards was brutal.  But those few, undiscovered moments had been worth the price.<br>
<br>
And so, she found herself in a new, more secure cell, (the one, she suspected, that had been intended for her all along) chained to the wall.  Awaiting the pleasure of the Dark Masters.  Based upon what she has seen of the Halls of the Dead, Centuri suspected her life would be short indeed once they no longer required her in one piece.  That Monster, Tyvlain Dy’Truin, had been by twice to gloat at her, his possessive gaze made her skin crawl.  She almost wished the Dark ones would kill her. Living long enough to be turned over to that demented fiend left a lot to be desired.<br>
<br>
But now, she had a hope.  Two actually, if Soulshiver had seen what had happened to her and was able to track her down.  She sent a silent prayer after her courier; the message must be delivered at all cost.   Small hopes, but they were enough to push back the darkness.  And, since she really had very little else left to lose….<br>
<br>
A bright, elven song of Praise to Tunare echoed sweetly down the dark hallways. The Masters seethed in rage, yet did nothing.  She was not yet expendable.<br>
